And so I conclude this history, having endeavored to preserve the memory of our past for future generations, that they may know the dealings of YHWH with our nation from the creation of the world until this present time.
Now I have completed my work in twenty books, and I pray that those who read these things may do so with understanding, and may judge fairly concerning the truth of what has been written.
After the death of Festus, Albinus succeeded him as procurator. But before he arrived, King Agrippa had given the high priesthood to Ananus the son of Ananus. This Ananus was a bold man and a leader of the Sadducees, who were very rigid in judging offenders. He assembled the Sanhedrin and brought before them James, the brother of Yeshua who was called the Anointed, and some others. He accused them of breaking the law and delivered them to be stoned.
Thus ended the history of our nation, from the creation until the twelfth year of the reign of Nero Caesar.
I, Flavius Josephus, a priest from Jerusalem, have written this history with great care, using both my own knowledge and the records of others, for the benefit of those who desire to know the truth about the Jewish people and their customs.

Book 19

Thus Claudius became emperor, and he immediately showed favor to the Jews, confirming the rights granted by previous emperors and appointing Agrippa over additional territories. So ended the reign of Caligula, whose madness had nearly brought destruction upon the whole empire and especially upon the nation of the Jews.
Agrippa, having been raised with the emperors, used his influence wisely and prevented many evils that Caligula had intended against the holy city and the temple. He persuaded the new emperor to restore peace and to honor the ancient customs of our people.
When news of Caligula’s death reached Jerusalem, there was great rejoicing among the people, for they had feared the emperor would set up his statue in the temple. But through the providence of YHWH and the efforts of Agrippa, the crisis was averted.
Caligula grew ever more insane, demanding that he be worshipped as a god and ordering his image to be placed in the Holy of Holies. Petronius the governor delayed carrying out the order, fearing the revolt of the Jews, and Agrippa interceded with the emperor on behalf of the nation.
In the meantime, the Jews throughout the empire suffered many afflictions under Caligula’s rule, yet they remained faithful to the laws of their fathers and refused to worship the emperor as a god.
This book has contained the history of the times of Gaius Caligula, who reigned four years, during which the Jewish nation was brought into the greatest danger, but was wonderfully delivered by the providence of YHWH.

Book 18

