Herod brought charges against his sons Alexander and Aristobulus before Augustus in Rome. Though they were temporarily reconciled, the hatred and suspicion in the family only grew worse, leading eventually to their execution.
Augustus received Herod with honor and confirmed his kingdom, but warned him to rule with greater moderation toward his own sons and subjects.
Herod sailed to Italy and met with Augustus, presenting gifts and defending his actions. Augustus reconciled him with his sons for a time and granted him additional favors.
In this period Herod undertook many great building projects, including the complete rebuilding of the Temple in Jerusalem with surpassing splendor, the founding of Caesarea, and the fortification of many cities throughout his realm.
This book has contained the history of the middle years of Herod the Great, his building projects, his alliances with Rome, and the growing conflicts within his own family that would eventually lead to great tragedy.

