Thus Aristobulus, having reigned for one year, died after much cruelty, and Alexander Jannaeus succeeded him, who warred against the neighboring nations and greatly expanded the borders of Judea, though his reign was marked by civil strife and bloodshed.
John Hyrcanus, having reigned in peace and prosperity for thirty-one years, died after destroying the Samaritan temple on Mount Gerizim and subduing many cities. He left the kingdom to his wife and eldest son Aristobulus.
Simon the high priest and his sons continued the work of their father Judas Maccabeus, cleansing the land of the heathen and establishing the independence of the Jewish nation. Simon was murdered by his son-in-law Ptolemy, and his son John Hyrcanus succeeded him.
