Nebuchadnezzar was humbled by YHWH, driven from men, eating grass like an ox, until he acknowledged that the Most High rules in the kingdom of men. After his restoration he praised the God of heaven.
In the days of Zedekiah, the last king of Judah, the city was besieged by Nebuchadnezzar. The walls were broken, the Temple burned, and the people carried captive to Babylon. Jeremiah prophesied these things but was not heeded.
Jehoiakim and Jehoiachin were carried to Babylon, and many of the vessels of the house of YHWH were taken. Daniel and his companions were taken among the captives and proved faithful in the king’s court.
This book has contained the history from the reign of Hezekiah through the destruction of Jerusalem and the Babylonian captivity, showing how the words of the prophets were fulfilled because the people forsook the covenant of YHWH.

Book 9

Thus the kingdom of Israel was utterly destroyed by the Assyrians, and the ten tribes were carried away captive beyond the river, never to return as a united nation. Judah alone remained, until its own sins brought destruction upon it.
Hezekiah, king of Judah, trusted in YHWH and kept His commandments. He cleansed the Temple, restored the Passover, and prayed when Sennacherib king of Assyria came against Jerusalem. The angel of YHWH struck down 185,000 in the Assyrian camp in one night, and Sennacherib returned to Nineveh in shame.
Jehoshaphat, king of Judah, walked in the ways of his father David and sought YHWH. He sent teachers throughout the land to teach the people the Law of YHWH, and YHWH gave him rest from his enemies.
The prophet Elisha performed many mighty works in Israel, including the healing of Naaman the Syrian of leprosy, the multiplying of the widow’s oil, and the raising of the Shunammite’s son from the dead. He also struck the Syrian army with blindness and led them into Samaria.
Ahaz king of Judah did not do what was right in the eyes of YHWH. He sacrificed to the gods of Damascus and shut the doors of the house of YHWH. Yet YHWH delivered Jerusalem from the kings of Israel and Syria for the sake of His servant David.
This book has contained the history from the division of the kingdom until the fall of the northern kingdom of Israel to the Assyrians, together with the reigns of the kings of Judah up to Hezekiah.

